               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270405-120-person761">
                  SOPHIA 
                  THOMAS
               <interp inst="t18270405-120-person761" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-120-person761" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-120-person761" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Thomas Thomas; he is a <rs id="t18270405-120-viclabel671" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270405-120-victim760 t18270405-120-viclabel671"></join>, and lives in Exeter-street, Strand. The prisoner lived with me for six weeks - she was a <rs id="t18270405-120-deflabel672" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270405-120-defend759 t18270405-120-deflabel672"></join>; when out of place she was in the habit of being with me. I have an aged mother very ill; and as I go out to ladies houses myself it is necessary I should have some one there with my mother. I left the prisoner there on Monday morning, the 12th of March, and desired her to get the dinner ready at twelve o'clock, against my husband came home. I went to Islington, and returned soon after eleven o'clock; I found the room door open: my drawers had been opened, and these articles taken from them; the prisoner was gone. I had seen them all safe the night before - my little girl had this pinafore on the day before - I have seen my property since.</p>
               <p>
            
